Text.Value: 'Tis a most curious mind yond enters a prison cell of its own will.
Nay sir hides within me. I am merely a skull, nay more and nay less.
Your first answer was correct, nonetheless. I will send you to the guards - but you will not go unrewarded.
Teleport me to safety.
A talking skull? I must be losing my mind.
Yes. Teleport me to safety.
You talk like a drunk poet. If you wish to converse, you need to speak plainly.
Examine the skull. What magic is at work?
Then begone with thee, and tradeth thy japes elsewhere!
Thy freedom is yours - thy safety is not. Such was mine gage.
I nev'r did sweat, even when the summertide sun didst fully heateth mine brow. Name me.
Teleport me out of here.
The spirit of a prankster had always dwelled in me. The game laid before you is born of jest, wizardry - and whiskey.
I wear only black, and run from the light. Yet without it, I couldn't exist. Who am I?
You answered me wisely. Off with you, then.
Answer them right, and I send you to safety. Answer them wrong, and I send you to the guards.
Answer me true, and I shall telep'rt thee to safety. Answer me false, and I shall telep'rt thee near the guards.
An anvil, indeed! You make me most proud.
Go on, ask your riddles.
*You can't fathom how this skull could be made to talk.*
I say thou art malapert to stare. But peradventure thou art new to such custom.
Such is mine own will. Once I did occupy this very prison after a night of most bacchanalian debauchery.
A shield.
Leave.
Alas, thou speaketh nay sooth to me. 'An anvil' was the answer.
Solve two riddles for me. A right answer, and I teleport you to safety. A wrong answer, and I teleport you to the guards.
The blame and the pleasure belong solely to me. A fine wizard I was, and a fine jester too, imprisoned for one night after a delightful rash of debauchery.
Thou hast returned? Mine own disappointment knows not its bounds.
Answer two riddles. Be true, and I teleport thee to safety. Be false, and I teleport thee to the guards.
Not yet.
Marvellous deduction - a shadow, forsooth! And anon, riddle the second.
I've no more riddles.
*Sigh.* Common is just so very - common.
Thou didst answereth so wise. Tis doneth.
I fly, yet not through the firmament. I bidst and biddeth and bidstseth farewell at night and welcome thee in the morn. I am part of thee, and follow whither thou guideth.
We shall speaketh at the most promising hour, but never ere.
I'm not playing this game with you.
Then we begin.
Hence with thee, then. Savour thy freedom, for thou cannot claim 't still. Away!
Thou wisheth to escape the confines of this prison, doth thou not? I can holpest thee for the cost of two riddles.
Leave.
This is ridiculous. Just get me out of here.
A shadow.
Poorly chosen, mine cousin. The correct answer was 'a shadow'.
Yet thou didst answer once truly. I wilt teleporteth thee into peril - but not without reguerdon.
I promised to free you, and so I shall. But I did not promise your safety.
Freedom is yours. Savour it, for there is no gift that cannot be reclaimed or ravaged. Away!
Must thy gaze pierce so deeply? Quite crude.
A king.
To the guards, as I promised. Begone!
Nay, thy mind hath not betrayed thee. I am as thou perceiveth.
I am clothened and claddened all in black, and flee the light. Yet apart 't, I wouldst be nought. Name me.
Now begone!
Leave.
I am done answering these silly riddles. Just free me already.
A child.
Anon begone - to the guards!
Unfortunate, nay, ineluctable, perchance evitable, to be confined in such immuring quarters.
Who's talking? Show yourself.
I fly, but not through the sky. I say goodbye at night and hello in the morning. I am part of you, and follow wherever you go.
I never sweat, even when the summertide sun shines upon me. Who am I?
Very well. To rephrase: I will teleport you away for the cost of two riddles.
I possessed the spirit of a gleeker and the art of a wizard.
*The enchantment is clearly the work of an advanced caster. The body may have wasted away, but the mind that inhabited it is imprinted on the skull.*
The merriment laid before thee is born of trifling jest, wizardry - and whiskey.
Pardon me?
How malapert. Must thou stareth so?

EditorData.NodeContext: All of the weird old ENglish is incorrect on purpose and should be spoken with great confidence

Text.Value: Is't thy will to forsake this decrepit cell?
Shouldst thee perform illicit acts, we wilt have much to break with.
To the guards, as was mine promise. Begone!
What a strange game you're playing. Who put you up to this?
We beginneth, to delight.
I call myself Marvin. Thou mayst do the same.
A shame - I thought you more clever. The true answer is 'a shadow'.
Alas, what tragedy. 'An anvil' was the answer.
Very good - your freedom is nigh. And now, the second riddle.
I am battered, but nev'r did bow. Mine coronet bears the blunt of endless blades, but I can nev'r move.
A raven.
An anvil.
An anvil, forsooth! Thou hast maketh me most fustian.
It is time to depart. Are you ready, good sir?
It is time to depart. Are you ready, madam?
It is time to depart. Are you ready?
Mine own words are already as kersey as the travelling lamp in the summer sky.
I am beaten and battered, but never break. My crown has felt the strike of endless blades, yet I can never move.
Alas, I speak only to the caged who cannot leave of their own accord.

Synopsis:
Dialog with the Talking Skull in Wyrm Rock Prison.
Belongs to a necromancer who died in this cell.
He used a spell to bind his soul to his skull.
Only interested in talking to prisoners, really.
